It appears that your folder (with gradle and all your code) is nested inside what VSCode thinks is your main folder. You can fix this by instead of opening FRC-Swerve-2021 you open FRC-Swerve-2021/FRC Swerve 2021 in vscode.

This is an easy mistake to make when cloning a repo in VS Code for the first time. When VS Code asks you to pick a directory to clone the repo into, you are choosing the parent directory where the repo’s directory will be put. Not the directory of the project itself.

Creating the directory yourself will put you in this situation where you have the project nested inside an identically name directory.

Not to say there aren’t other ways to get into this situation, but I’ve found this to be a common mistake (and one I’ve made as well).

As pointed out above, the actual cause of your error message is you need to have VS Code opening the project folder, and not the parent folder so it knows where to find all the gradle files.
